data.name: toolStripMenuItem_PredefinedContextMenu_CopyTextOrFilePath.ToolTipText
data.value:
Only copies the command's text or file path to the clipboard.
This action is different than the other cut/copy/paste actions. The other actions apply to a complete command, a command's complete XML definition including description, default radix, command variant and state will be cut/copied/pasted. This action only applies to the command's text or file path.

data.name: toolStripMenuItem_SendContextMenu_AllowConcurrency.ToolTipText
data.value: By default, commands are sent strictly sequentially, i.e. only one command can be active at a time. Enabling this option allows multiple commands being active simultaneously. Useful e.g. for sending a text command while a repeating text command is already ongoing. Applies to [Send Text], [Send File] as well as [Predefined Commands].

data.name: toolStripComboBox_TerminalMenu_Send_AutoResponse_Trigger.ToolTipText
data.value:
Configure Automatic Response Trigger, either refer to one of the commands, or fill-in any text, optionally including a regular expression.
Some useful regular expression capture patterns (use without surrounding quotes): Integral numbers: "([-+]?\d+)" Floating point numbers in normal format: "([-+]?(?:\d+(?:\.\d*)?|\.\d+))" Floating point numbers in scientific format: "([-+]?(?:\d+(?:\.\d*)?|\.\d+)[Ee][-+]?\d+)" Floating point numbers in any format: "([-+]?(?:\d+(?:\.\d*)?|\.\d+)(?:[Ee][-+]?\d+)?)" Time with colons (e.g. 12:00:00): "((?:[01]\d|2[0-3]):(?:[0-5]\d):(?:[0-5]\d))" Date with hyphens (e.g. 2000-01-01): "((?:19|20)\d\d-(?:0[1-9]|1[012])-(?:0[1-9]|[12]\d|3[01]))" A single capital letter: "\b([A-Z]{1})\b" A string of 2..4 letters: "\b([A-Za-z]{2,4})\b"
Google for ".NET Regular Expression Quick Reference" for details on syntax.

data.name: toolStripMenuItem_TerminalMenu_Send_AutoResponse_Response_EnableReplace.ToolTipText
data.value:
Requires that trigger uses text with enabled regular expression, because replacement is done based on regular expression captures.
Example usage: > Trigger = (\d+)ABC > Response = $1XYZ Receiving e.g. 99ABC will trigger the response, 99 being captured by (\d+). The $1 replacement tag will be filled with 99, resulting in sending 99XYZ.
Replacement tags are $1, $2,... (regular expression syntax).

data.name: toolStripComboBox_TerminalMenu_Receive_AutoAction_Trigger.ToolTipText
data.value:
Configure Automatic Action Trigger, either refer to one of the commands, or fill-in any text, optionally including a regular expression.
Some useful regular expression capture patterns (use without surrounding quotes): Integral numbers: "([-+]?\d+)" Floating point numbers in normal format: "([-+]?(?:\d+(?:\.\d*)?|\.\d+))" Floating point numbers in scientific format: "([-+]?(?:\d+(?:\.\d*)?|\.\d+)[Ee][-+]?\d+)" Floating point numbers in any format: "([-+]?(?:\d+(?:\.\d*)?|\.\d+)(?:[Ee][-+]?\d+)?)" Time with colons (e.g. 12:00:00): "((?:[01]\d|2[0-3]):(?:[0-5]\d):(?:[0-5]\d))" Date with hyphens (e.g. 2000-01-01): "((?:19|20)\d\d-(?:0[1-9]|1[012])-(?:0[1-9]|[12]\d|3[01]))" A single capital letter: "\b([A-Z]{1})\b" A string of 2..4 letters: "\b([A-Za-z]{2,4})\b"
Google for ".NET Regular Expression Quick Reference" for details on syntax.
Note that... ...[Any Line] is not available if action is [Highlight] or [Suppress], as that would otherwise result in all received lines being highlighted or suppressed. ...same as other actions, [Filter] and [Suppress] are only applied to received data. ...only [Plot ... Count/Rate] are also applied to sent data.

data.name: toolStripComboBox_TerminalMenu_Receive_AutoAction_Action.ToolTipText
data.value:
Enable / Disable Automatic Action
[Line/Scatter/Histogram] require that trigger is based on a regular expression, as the regular expression captures (e.g. "([-+]?\d+)") are used to retrieve the values to plot. All captures will be treated as Y values, unless for action stating "(X = Time)" where the first capture will be treated as the X value. Date/Time values are converted to "OLE Automation Date" values. Google that term for details. Captures that can neither be converted to an integral or floating point number, nor a date/time value, are treated as strings. Strings are converted to a value by summing the code of each character. This allows plotting elements defined by characters (e.g. A, B, C) or even whole strings.
Note that... ...trigger is highlighted for every action except [Filter], [Suppress] and [Line/Scatter/Histogram]. ...[Highlight] and [Suppress] is not available if trigger is [Any Line], as that would otherwise result in all received lines being highlighted or suppressed. ...same as other actions, [Filter] and [Suppress] are only applied to received data. ...only [Plot ... Count/Rate] are also applied to sent data.
